04435nam a22006375i 9781477306314DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211969txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814773063147 a10.7560/7841302doi  a(DE-B1597)588214  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aKF2439.R4 7aLAW0000002bisacsh1 aRedford, Emmette S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Regulatory Process :bWith Illustrations from Commercial Aviation /cEmmette S. Redford. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1969  a1 online resource (346 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tPREFACE -- tCONTENTS -- tTABLES -- tPart I. Interpretive Essays -- t1. Perspectives for the Study of Government Regulation -- t2 The Significance of Belief Patterns in Economic Regulation: The Civil Aeronautics Act of 1938 -- t3 Congress and Regulation: Civil Aviation, 1957—1958 -- tPart II. Case Narratives -- t4 Policy Evolves: Congress, the Executive, and a Trade Association -- t5 An Administrative Center at Work: The CAB's General Passenger Fare Investigation -- t6 The Air Transport Association -- tPart III. Evaluation -- t7 An Essay in Evaluation -- tBibliography of Cited Materials -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe subject of regulation is one of the most vital and troublesome in our system of government. In this detailed study of early and mid-twentieth-century regulation of commercial aviation Emmette S. Redford illustrates what happens when government regulates a particular industry. He first sets forth the perspectives for a study of an area of regulation and develops an argument for eclectic perspectives in the study of selected systems, or universes, of social action, such as the performance of an economic function under government regulation. These perspectives are illustrated in the following series of case studies on regulation of commercial aviation: The significance of belief patterns on the content of the Civil Aeronautics Act of 1938. The role of Congress in the regulation of commercial aviation in a two-year period. The interactions of Congress, the president, and the regulated industry in strengthening safety regulation through passage of the Federal Aviation Act of 1958. The actions of the Civil Aeronautics Board on a set of complicated economic issues in the General Passenger Fare Investigation. The position of the Air Transport Association in the regulatory pattern. In "An Essay on Evaluation" Redford summarizes what is revealed in the case studies that is significant with respect to the system of government regulation. He searches for standards for evaluating a system of social control, or for evaluating parts of it, and relates his conclusions to issues regarding the beneficence of a system of regulated private supply of a service. The Regulatory Process is a study of interest to the aviation industry, to students of regulation of the economy, and to those who seek an understanding of social systems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/78413040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477306314423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477306314/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK